1095. Find in Mountain Array
You may recall that an array arr is a mountain array if and only if:
arr.length >= 3
There exists some i with 0 < i < arr.length - 1 such that:
arr[0] < arr[1] < ... < arr[i - 1] < arr[i]
arr[i] > arr[i + 1] > ... > arr[arr.length - 1]
Given a mountain array mountainArr, return the minimum index such that mountainArr.get(index) == target. If such an index does not exist, return -1.

You cannot access the mountain array directly. You may only access the array using a MountainArray interface:

MountainArray.get(k) returns the element of the array at index k (0-indexed).
MountainArray.length() returns the length of the array.
Submissions making more than 100 calls to MountainArray.get will be judged Wrong Answer. Also, any solutions that attempt to circumvent the judge will result in disqualification.

 
Example 1:
Input: mountainArr = [1,2,3,4,5,3,1], target = 3
Output: 2
Explanation: 3 exists in the array, at index=2 and index=5. Return the minimum index, which is 2.

Example 2:
Input: mountainArr = [0,1,2,4,2,1], target = 3
Output: -1
Explanation: 3 does not exist in the array, so we return -1.
 
Constraints:
3 <= mountainArr.length() <= 104
0 <= target <= 109
0 <= mountainArr.get(index) <= 109


Solution:-


/**
 * // This is MountainArray's API interface.
 * // You should not implement it, or speculate about its implementation
 * interface MountainArray {
 *     public int get(int index) {}
 *     public int length() {}
 * }
 */
 //Approach
 //===Find the peak element then check if target element is greater than peak or less than peak
 //if less than peak end=peakindex-1
 //if greater than peak start=peakindex+1
class Solution {
        public int findPeakElement(MountainArray arr) {    ////Fucntion for finding the peak Index
        int start=0;
        int end=arr.length()-1;
        int peak=0;

        while(start<end){
            int mid=start+(end-start)/2;

            if(arr.get(mid)<arr.get(mid+1)){
                start=mid+1;
            }else{
                end=mid;
            }
        }
      //When start and end will be equal to they will be pointing to the maximum value or peak element of the array
        return start;
    }
    public int BinarySearchOrder(MountainArray arr, int target, int start, int end){ //Binary Search Agnostic Order
        boolean isAsc=(arr.get(start) < arr.get(end));

        while(start<=end){
            int mid=start+(end-start)/2;
             if(arr.get(mid)==target){
                return mid;
             }
             if(isAsc){
                 if(arr.get(mid)<target){
                        end=mid-1;
                    }else{
                       start=mid+1;
                    }
                }else{
                     if(arr.get(mid)>target){
                        end=mid-1;
                    }else{
                       start=mid+1;
                    }
                }
             
        }
        return -1;
    }
    public int findInMountainArray(int target, MountainArray mountainArr) {
        int indexpos=-1;
        //find peak index
        int peakIndex=findPeakElement(mountainArr);
        int firstTry=BinarySearchOrder(mountainArr,target,0,peakIndex);
          if(firstTry != -1){
            return firstTry;
          }
          return BinarySearchOrder(mountainArr,target,peakIndex+1,mountainArr.length()-1);
         
    }
}
